  "title": "Gas evolution",
  "family": "gas-evolution",
  "general_form": "acid + carbonate (or ammonium salt + base) -> salt + water + gas",
  "summary": "A double replacement would form an unstable product that immediately breaks down and releases a gas — that gas escaping is the driving force. A carbonate plus an acid makes carbonic acid, which falls apart into water and carbon dioxide; an ammonium salt plus a base makes aqueous ammonia, which releases ammonia gas. No element goes free, so it is not a redox reaction.",
  "regime": "rule-sourced",
  "source": "openstax-chemistry-2e",
  "conditions": [
    "The trigger is a would-be product that is unstable: carbonic acid (from a carbonate) or aqueous ammonia (from an ammonium salt + base).",
    "The gas leaving the solution is what pulls the reaction forward."
  ],
  "misconceptions": [
    {
      "claim": "Carbonic acid (H2CO3) is one of the final products.",
      "refute": "It forms for an instant, then decomposes — the products you actually collect are water and carbon dioxide gas. The Atlas shows the two-step logic behind the single written equation."
    },
    {
      "claim": "The bubbles are just the solvent boiling.",
      "refute": "The gas is a real product of the reaction (CO2 or NH3), formed atom-for-atom from the reactants — count them in the balanced equation. It is chemistry, not heat."
    }
  ],
